n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:58:\"Beginner’s Guide to User Permissions in Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:187:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:96:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 06 Dec 2018 17:14:05 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"MonsterInsights Permissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"Google Analytics user permissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"Google Analytics permission levels\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=174329\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:659:\"<p>Want to learn how to use and manage user permissions in Google Analytics? Understanding user permissions is crucial while sharing access to your Google Analytics account or data with other people as it concerns with the safety, privacy, and the overall growth strategies of your business(es). In this article, we’ll explain everything you need to [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide to User Permissions in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17373:\"<p>Want to learn how to use and manage user permissions in Google Analytics? Understanding user permissions is crucial while sharing access to your Google Analytics account or data with other people as it concerns with the safety, privacy, and the overall growth strategies of your business(es). </p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll explain everything you need to know about Google Analytics user permissions and how to manage them easily. </p>\n<h3>What Are User Permissions in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>In Google Analytics, you can add other people from your team as users and allow them access to your Analytics account or data at different levels. Such different levels of access to your Analytics account or data are called ‘user permissions’. User permissions refer to the types of privileges a user gets in a Google Analytics account.</p>\n<p>For example, you as the owner of your Analytics account can view all the data, add, edit, and manage website properties, add users and manage them. However, you may not want to give the same level of access to another person. That’s what user permissions are designed for. </p>\n<p>User permissions allow you to provide a certain level of access to certain users. Using them, you can <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-grant-access-to-your-account-and-share-google-analytics-reports/\">grant access to your Analytics data and share useful reports</a>. </p>\n<p>Thus you should carefully decide whom you want to give editing access, managing access, or view only access. User permissions help you to share data while also ensuring your full control over your account management and data usage.</p>\n<p>Google Analytics allows you to provide 4 types of user permissions at 3 levels. Let’s first start with the permission levels.</p>\n<h3>Google Analytics Permission Levels</h3>\n<p>Google Analytics lets you provide permissions at 3 different levels of your Google Analytics account. The levels of user permissions are based on the hierarchical structure of Google Analytics organization.  </p>\n<p><strong>1. Account Level</strong></p>\n<p>An account is the top-most level of organization which can include multiple properties (websites) and multiple views. </p>\n<p>Providing access at account level means allowing access to all the properties and views in your account. </p>\n<p><strong>2. Property Level</strong></p>\n<p>A property is typically a website. There can be multiple views under one property. </p>\n<p>For example, all website data for https://yoursite.com can be one view whereas only traffic to the subdomain https://blog.yoursite.com can be another view.  </p>\n<p>Providing access at property level means allowing access to all the views in your property/website.</p>\n<p><strong>3. View Level</strong></p>\n<p>A view is a subset of an Analytics account property. It allows access to only a defined view of data from a website property. </p>\n<p>For example; you may want to allow access to only the subdomain view i.e. https://blog.yoursite.com to a content writer in your team. </p>\n<p>That’s why you’ll see <strong>User Management</strong> option in all three levels of your Analytics admin options. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg\" alt=\"user-management-ga-3-levels\" width=\"620\" height=\"292\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174342\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels-300x141.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>Types of Google Analytics User Permissions</h3>\n<p>There&#8217;re 4 types of user permissions you can provide at each level discussed above.<br />\n<strong>1. Manage Users</strong></p>\n<p>Users with this permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add and delete users</li>\n<li>Manage users and grant full permissions to anyone including themselves</li>\n</ul>\n<p>However this permission doesn’t include edit or collaborate permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>2. Edit</strong></p>\n<p>Users with <strong>Edit</strong> permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete accounts, properties, and views as per the permission level</li>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete goals</li>\n<li>Create/ edit custom dimensions and metrics (Edit permission at property level is required)</li>\n<li>Connect Adwords, Search Console, and other products (Edit permission at property level is required)</li>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete filters (Edit permission at account level permission is required)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It includes all permissions from <strong>Collaborate</strong> and <strong>Read and Analyze</strong> permissions but not <strong>Manage Users</strong> permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>3. Collaborate</strong></p>\n<p>Users with <strong>Collaborate</strong> permission can perform the following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create, edit, delete, and share personal assets</li>\n<li>Collaborate on shared assets like custom reports, dashboards, segments, etc. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>It includes all permissions from <strong>Read and Analyze</strong> but not <strong>Manage Users</strong> and <strong>Edit</strong> permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>4.Read and Analyze</strong></p>\n<p>Users with this permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>View reports</li>\n<li>Manipulate data within reports like filtering a table, adding secondary dimension, create a segment, etc.</li>\n<li>See shared assets however cannot collaborate on them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It doesn’t include any of the permissions discussed above. </p>\n<h3>Understanding Permission Types at Permission Levels</h3>\n<p>The users can perform actions on only the levels for which they have these permissions. For example, if a user is allowed <strong>Manage Users</strong> permission at <strong>Account</strong> level, they can add, manage, and delete users in the account, in all website properties, and views. However a user with <strong>Manage Users</strong> permission at <strong>View</strong> level can add, manage, and delete users for only 1 view they’ve permission for. </p>\n<p>Normally you may not want to allow <strong>Manage Users</strong> or <strong>Edit</strong> permission at <strong>Account</strong> level to anyone except your business partner with equal share.</p>\n<h3>How to Add Users and Manage Permissions in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>Now that you know user permissions and levels, you may want to know how to add users and manage permissions. Next, we’ll show you how to do that. </p>\n<p>To get started, you’ll need to sign in to your Google Analytics account. Then, click <strong>Admin</strong> option at the bottom of your Analytics panel in the left.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg\" alt=\"ga-admin\" width=\"250\" height=\"586\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169257\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg 250w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin-128x300.jpg 128w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see the 3 levels of access i.e. Account, Property, and View. And, you’ll also find <strong>User Management</strong> option below all 3 access levels. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg\" alt=\"user-management-ga-3-levels\" width=\"620\" height=\"292\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174342\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels-300x141.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Navigate to your desired level Account or Property or View and click the <strong>User Management</strong> option. </p>\n<p>Then, you’ll see the list of users with a brief summary of the permissions allowed to them. </p>\n<p>Click the <strong>+ (Plus)</strong> icon to add new users. Select <strong>Add New Users</strong> option. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga.jpg\" alt=\"add-new-user-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"193\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174343\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga-300x93.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see a new page where you can add new users and assign permissions. </p>\n<p>First, enter the email address you want to add. If you want to add multiple users with the same type of permissions, you can enter the email addresses separated by the comma. </p>\n<p>Select <strong>Notify new users by email</strong> option. And, select the permissions you want to allow. Then, click the <strong>Add</strong> button. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga.jpg\" alt=\"add-permissions-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"469\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174344\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga-300x227.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>That’s it! You’ve successfully added a new user(s) to your Analytics account. Now they’ll be able to view, edit, collaborate or manage users in your Analytics account as per the permissions you provided. </p>\n<h3>How to Edit and Delete Users in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>If you want to edit any user’s permissions, you can go to the list of users by navigating to <strong>Admin &raquo; User Management</strong> from Account, Property or View level. </p>\n<p>Then, navigate to the user’s name in the list you want to edit and click on it. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga.jpg\" alt=\"edit-users-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"208\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174345\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga-300x101.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, you can select and deselect user permissions as you like. Once you add or remove permissions, click the <strong>Save</strong> button. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga.jpg\" alt=\"save-user-permissions-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"538\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174346\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga-300x260.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to remove the user, you can click the <strong>Remove</strong> button next to the <strong>Save</strong> button. </p>\n<p>If you want to delete multiple users at once, you can go to the list of users from <strong>Admin &raquo; User Management</strong>. Then, select the users you want to delete and click the <strong>Remove</strong> button at the top of right side. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga.jpg\" alt=\"remove-users-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"206\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174349\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga-300x100.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>EASY Way to Managing User Permissions in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The easiest way to manage your Google Analytics user permissions in WordPress is using <strong>Permissions</strong> option in <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> plugin. </p>\n<p>The MonsterInsights Permissions allows you to assign your WordPress users the permissions to view reports and save settings in Google Analytics dashboard reports inside WordPress. And you can do that in just 2 easy clicks of your mouse.</p>\n<p>However, this method is exclusively useful only for WordPress sites that are using MonsterInsights to use Google Analytics. </p>\n<p>So before we show you the steps, you&#8217;ll need to make sure that you’ve connected your site with your Google Analytics account using MonsterInsights. If you need instructions, here’s our step-by-step guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to properly set up Google Analytics in WordPress using MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve completed the setup process, you can go to <strong>Insights &raquo; Settings</strong> and click the <strong>Tracking</strong> tab. Then, scroll down to the end where you’ll find <strong>Permissions</strong> section. Click on that.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171106\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings.jpg\" alt=\"mi-permissions-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"700\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings-266x300.jpg 266w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can allow permissions to view your Google Analytics reports and save settings to the selected user roles.</p>\n<p>All you need to do to share access to see the reports is to select the user roles.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171107\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"404\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports-300x195.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Similarly, select the user roles whom you want to grant access to both view and save settings.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171108\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings.jpg\" alt=\"mi-let-users-save-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"531\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings-300x257.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, don’t forget to hit <strong>Save Changes</strong>.</p>\n<p>That’s it! Now your selected user roles (administrators, editors, authors, or other user roles) will get access to your Google Analytics dashboard reports and settings by going to <strong>Insights</strong> menu in the WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><strong>A Few Words About MonsterInsights</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re wondering why would anyone want to use MonsterInsights, here&#8217;re a few words. First, it makes Google Analytics super simple for WordPress website owners. It lets you install and use Google Analytics in WordPress effortlessly.</p>\n<p>Second, the plugin helps you to track your most important Google Analytics metrics and provides you with the extremely comprehensive reports. Best of all, you can view all your <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/google-analytics-dashboard/\">reports right in your WordPress dashboard</a> without having to navigate away to other sites.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s the most popular, user-friendly Google Analytics WordPress plugin available on the market. </p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you learn about Google Analytics user permissions and how to manage them.</p>\n<p>You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/\">how to share your Google Analytics reports with others</a>.</p>\n<p>Don’t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide to User Permissions in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:93:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"How to Add a Countdown Timer in WordPress to Boost Sales\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:159:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 03 Dec 2018 19:11:12 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"conversion optimization\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"optinmonster tutorial\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:38:\"countdown timer campaign for WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=173937\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:581:\"<p>Want to add a countdown timer in WordPress? A countdown timer creates a sense of urgency and entices your users to take action immediately before the time is up. So, if you’re running an online store, adding a countdown timer is a smart way to invite users to buy a product at the spur of [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress/\">How to Add a Countdown Timer in WordPress to Boost Sales</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23524:\"<p>Want to add a countdown timer in WordPress? A countdown timer creates a sense of urgency and entices your users to take action immediately before the time is up. So, if you’re running an online store, adding a countdown timer is a smart way to invite users to buy a product at the spur of the moment. It’s a great technique to boost sales.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to easily add a countdown timer in WordPress, step-by-step.</p>\n<h3>Adding a Countdown Timer in WordPress with OptinMonster</h3>\n<p>Creating a countdown timer on your online store helps tremendously to convert more visitors into customers. That’s because a countdown timer gives your users a clear deadline and a compelling reason to buy. They urge users to take action NOW.</p>\n<p>However, while countdown timers can certainly help to boost conversions, the process of creating one and adding it to your site can be a tough task&#8230; unless you have the right tool. That’s why the world&#8217;s most popular lead generation software, <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">OptinMonster</a>, has come up with an easy solution.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-155241\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/optinmonster-conversion-optimization-software.jpg\" alt=\"optinmonster-conversion-optimization-software\" width=\"560\" height=\"260\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/optinmonster-conversion-optimization-software.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/optinmonster-conversion-optimization-software-300x139.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></a></p>\n<p>OptinMonster is the best lead generation and conversion optimization software on the market. It has powerful tools and features to convert more visitors into subscribers and customers.</p>\n<p>Plus, OptinMonster now comes with a pre-designed <strong>countdown timer </strong>campaign template to allow you quickly build a countdown timer for your WordPress website. You can also add the countdown element block to any template and totally transform it into a countdown campaign.</p>\n<p>Let’s go ahead and see how to create and add a countdown timer to your WordPress site using OptinMonster (step-by-step).</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a Countdown Campaign</h3>\n<p>First of all, login to your OptinMonster dashboard. You’ll need a <strong>Pro</strong> plan for Countdown Timers, so make sure that you have a Pro plan license or better.</p>\n<p>Then, click the <strong>Create Campaign</strong> button to get started.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173963\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/create-campaign-om.jpg\" alt=\"create-campaign-om\" width=\"620\" height=\"121\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/create-campaign-om.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/create-campaign-om-300x59.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to choose a campaign type. Here, we’ll choose <strong>Floating Bar</strong> because it includes a pre-made <strong>countdown timer theme</strong>. However, you can find other themes with the countdown timer block within other campaign types as well.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173964\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-campaign-type.jpg\" alt=\"select-campaign-type\" width=\"620\" height=\"229\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-campaign-type.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-campaign-type-300x111.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, choose the <strong>Countdown</strong> template by hovering over it and clicking on the <strong>Use Template</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173965\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-campaign-template.jpg\" alt=\"choose-campaign-template\" width=\"620\" height=\"347\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-campaign-template.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-campaign-template-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, a new page will appear where you’ll need to name your campaign and select the website(s) you want to load the campaign on. Then, click the <strong>Start Building</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173966\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/start-building-countdown-timer-campaign.jpg\" alt=\"start-building-countdown-timer-campaign\" width=\"620\" height=\"408\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/start-building-countdown-timer-campaign.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/start-building-countdown-timer-campaign-300x197.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see your campaign builder interface along with the default Countdown campaign.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173967\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/optinmonster-campaign-builder.jpg\" alt=\"optinmonster-campaign-builder\" width=\"620\" height=\"359\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/optinmonster-campaign-builder.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/optinmonster-campaign-builder-300x174.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 2: Configure the Design Options</h3>\n<p>At first, you’ll see the <strong>Design</strong> options are selected. Here we&#8217;ll show you how to configure them.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173968\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-countdown-design-settings.jpg\" alt=\"om-countdown-design-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"359\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-countdown-design-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-countdown-design-settings-300x174.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>First, there’re <strong>Optin Settings</strong> which include options to change your Countdown background and styles for the close button.</p>\n<p><strong>Blocks</strong> include the different column blocks and element blocks including text, image, button, video, and Countdown. If you want to add more blocks to the default campaign template provided, you can drag them to the campaign template in the right-hand side.</p>\n<p><strong>Display Settings</strong> include options for cookies, and to display or hide the <strong>Powered by OptinMonster</strong> link, etc.</p>\n<p><strong>Floating Settings</strong> include an option to show the floating bar at the top of the page. All you need to do is to toggle on <strong> Load floating bar at the top of the page</strong> option.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173969\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/floating-bar-at-top.jpg\" alt=\"floating-bar-at-top\" width=\"620\" height=\"263\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/floating-bar-at-top.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/floating-bar-at-top-300x127.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, click the <strong>Save</strong> button to save the changes.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173984\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-countdown-timer.jpg\" alt=\"save-countdown-timer\" width=\"620\" height=\"99\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-countdown-timer.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-countdown-timer-300x48.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Make sure to click the <strong>Save</strong> button frequently to prevent loss of your data and settings.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Edit and customize your Countdown Campaign</h3>\n<p>Editing OptinMonster campaigns is easy as it integrates visual editor interface fully. So, you can click directly on any element to edit.</p>\n<p>For example, click the countdown clock to edit it.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173973\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-timer.jpg\" alt=\"edit-countdown-timer\" width=\"620\" height=\"209\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-timer.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-timer-300x101.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>First, you can choose a countdown type. There’re 2 different countdown timer modes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Static:</strong> If you choose Static timer, the timer will look the same to everyone who visits your site.</li>\n<li><strong>Dynamic:</strong> With a dynamic countdown, each user will see a different countdown which starts as soon as the visitor comes to the page. Instead of setting an ending date, you set the length of the timer in the number of days, hours, minutes, and seconds.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In this example, we’re choosing <strong>Static</strong> and setting up end date and time.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173974\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/editing-countdown-timer-optinmonster.jpg\" alt=\"editing-countdown-timer-optinmonster\" width=\"620\" height=\"537\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/editing-countdown-timer-optinmonster.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/editing-countdown-timer-optinmonster-300x260.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After it’s done, click the text box for editing. Then, you’ll see the editor on the left side panel. Simply customize the text, font styles, and save your changes.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173975\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-text-om.jpg\" alt=\"edit-countdown-text-om\" width=\"620\" height=\"295\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-text-om.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-countdown-text-om-300x143.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Similarly, edit your email field and submit button.</p>\n<p>Once you’ve customized everything on your campaign template, go ahead and click the <strong>Save</strong> button again.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Set Up Display Rules</h3>\n<p>Now the next step is to set up your countdown timer display rules.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Display Rules</strong> tab on the top.</p>\n<p>Now you can set up conditions when to display the countdown timer. By default settings, the timer will appear after a user stays at least 5 seconds on a page. You can change it from the dropdowns and also add more rule sets to display the timer.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173976\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/display-rules.jpg\" alt=\"display-rules\" width=\"620\" height=\"638\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/display-rules.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/display-rules-292x300.jpg 292w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Once you set the display rules, click the <strong>Save</strong> button again.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Connect an Email Service Provider</h3>\n<p>In order to collect emails, you need to connect your OptinMonster campaign with an email service provider. The good news is that OptinMonster has built-in integration with all the major email service providers.</p>\n<p>To add your email integration, click the <strong>Integrations</strong> tab on the top menu. Then click <strong>Add New Integration</strong> button in the left-hand side panel.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173977\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-integration.jpg\" alt=\"add-new-integration\" width=\"620\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-integration.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-integration-300x109.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, select an email provider where you’ve your email list. In this tutorial, we’re choosing MailChimp.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173978\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-email-provider.jpg\" alt=\"select-email-provider\" width=\"620\" height=\"311\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-email-provider.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-email-provider-300x150.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, click <strong>Add New Account</strong> option. Enter a MailChimp account label and a MailChimp API key. You can find the API key on your MailChimp account page.</p>\n<p>After that, click the <strong>Connect to Mailchimp</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173979\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-mailchimp.jpg\" alt=\"connect-mailchimp\" width=\"257\" height=\"543\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-mailchimp.jpg 257w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-mailchimp-142x300.jpg 142w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 257px) 100vw, 257px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to select your email list where you want to save your new campaign emails.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173980\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-email-list.jpg\" alt=\"choose-email-list\" width=\"257\" height=\"363\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-email-list.jpg 257w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/choose-email-list-212x300.jpg 212w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 257px) 100vw, 257px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, click the <strong>Next</strong> button again.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Publish Your Countdown Timer Campaign</h3>\n<p>Now that you’ve configured all the available options, you’re finally ready to publish your countdown timer on your site.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Publish</strong> tab and click on it. Then toggle the <strong>Paused</strong> status to <strong>Live</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173981\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/publish-countdown.jpg\" alt=\"publish-countdown\" width=\"620\" height=\"290\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/publish-countdown.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/publish-countdown-300x140.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can add the countdown timer to different platforms including WordPress.</p>\n<p>Adding your OptinMonster countdown timer to WordPress is very easy with the OptinMonster API plugin. Simply install and activate the plugin on your WordPress dashboard and then click the <strong>OptinMonster</strong> menu in your WordPress dashboard panel.</p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see the list of campaigns. If you can’t see the latest one, click the <strong>Refresh Campaigns</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173982\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/refresh-campains-wp-dashboard.jpg\" alt=\"refresh-campains-wp-dashboard\" width=\"620\" height=\"243\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/refresh-campains-wp-dashboard.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/refresh-campains-wp-dashboard-300x118.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Once it appears, click the <strong>Go Live</strong> button to make the Countdown timer go live on your WordPress site.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173983\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/go-live-countdown-counter.jpg\" alt=\"go-live-countdown-counter\" width=\"620\" height=\"360\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/go-live-countdown-counter.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/go-live-countdown-counter-300x174.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>That’s it. Now you can open your website frontend and view the countdown timer you’ve just added.</p>\n<h3>Track Your Countdown Campaign with Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>OptinMonster integrates the most popular web analytics tool Google Analytics to provide you with the analytics reports on how your campaigns are performing. Now you can see the complete statistics on clicks, views, and conversion rate for each of your OptinMonster campaigns.</p>\n<p>To enable tracking for your Countdown timer, you’ll need to connect it with your Google Analytics account.</p>\n<p>Go to the <strong>Analytics</strong> tab from the top menu and click on it. Then, click the <strong>Connect</strong> button next to Google Analytics.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173985\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-to-optinmonster-campaign.jpg\" alt=\"connect-ga-to-optinmonster-campaign\" width=\"620\" height=\"299\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-to-optinmonster-campaign.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-to-optinmonster-campaign-300x145.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you’ll see this message “We need to authenticate your Google Analytics Account with OptinMonster before we can enable Google Analytics tracking for your campaign campaigns.”</p>\n<p>So, you’ll need to click the <strong>Generate Authentication Code</strong> button to continue.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173986\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generate-authentication-code-ga-with-om.jpg\" alt=\"generate-authentication-code-ga-with-om\" width=\"620\" height=\"299\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generate-authentication-code-ga-with-om.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generate-authentication-code-ga-with-om-300x145.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then a new window will open asking you to continue with your Google Analytics account. If you’ve signed into multiple Google accounts, make sure to select an account associated with your Analytics account. Then, click <strong>Allow</strong> button to allow OptinMonster an access to your Analytics account.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173987\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/allow-access-optinmonster.jpg\" alt=\"allow-access-optinmonster\" width=\"620\" height=\"459\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/allow-access-optinmonster.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/allow-access-optinmonster-300x222.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you’ll see a line of code generated. Copy the code.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173988\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generated-code-for-om.jpg\" alt=\"generated-code-for-om\" width=\"620\" height=\"179\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generated-code-for-om.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/generated-code-for-om-300x87.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, return to the Analytics option in your OptinMonster dashboard and paste the code in the Google Analytics authentication code field.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173991\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-with-code.jpg\" alt=\"connect-ga-with-code\" width=\"620\" height=\"206\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-with-code.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/connect-ga-with-code-300x100.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Also enter your Analytics account label and click <strong>Next</strong> button. Next, you can choose <strong>All Web Site Data</strong> from your website profile.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173992\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-analytics-website-profile.jpg\" alt=\"select-analytics-website-profile\" width=\"620\" height=\"206\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-analytics-website-profile.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/select-analytics-website-profile-300x100.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, go ahead and click the <strong>Next</strong> button.</p>\n<p>After that, you’ll see a success message regarding your fully connected Google Analytics to OptinMonster.</p>\n<p>That’s it! If you’re wondering how to view your Analytics reports, you can go to <strong>Campaigns</strong> list page in your OptinMonster dashboard and click the <strong>Arrow</strong> icon beside your countdown campaign.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173993\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaigns-analytics-icon.jpg\" alt=\"om-campaigns-analytics-icon\" width=\"620\" height=\"349\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaigns-analytics-icon.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaigns-analytics-icon-300x169.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, a new screen will open where you can see the reports like the one below:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173994\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaign-data.jpg\" alt=\"om-campaign-data\" width=\"620\" height=\"349\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaign-data.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/om-campaign-data-300x169.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to add a countdown timer in WordPress to boost sales.</p>\n<p>You may also want to see our guide on the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/ecommerce-email-marketing-best-practices-to-grow-sales/\">best eCommerce email marketing practices to grow sales</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, don’t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress/\">How to Add a Countdown Timer in WordPress to Boost Sales</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:79:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-countdown-timer-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"How to Create Custom Alerts in Google Analytics (Beginner’s Guide)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:171:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-custom-alerts-in-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-create-custom-alerts-in-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:88:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-custom-alerts-in-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 29 Nov 2018 22:36:48 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"Google Analytics dashboards\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"MonsterInsights Dashboards\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:30:\"Google Analytics custom alerts\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=173362\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:649:\"<p>Want to create custom alerts in Google Analytics? The Google Analytics alerts you set up help you keep track of major changes in your website traffic, user interactions, and conversions on your site. Thanks to timely alerts, you can immediately catch and then solve the problems that&#8217;re causing harm to your site before it’s too [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-custom-alerts-in-google-analytics/\">How to Create Custom Alerts in Google Analytics (Beginner&#8217;s Guide)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11023:\"<p>Want to create custom alerts in Google Analytics? The Google Analytics alerts you set up help you keep track of major changes in your website traffic, user interactions, and conversions on your site. Thanks to timely alerts, you can immediately catch and then solve the problems that&#8217;re causing harm to your site before it’s too late.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to create and manage custom alerts in Google Analytics step-by-step.</p>\n<h3>Why Track Google Analytics Custom Alerts?</h3>\n<p>Have you ever noticed a sudden drop or spike in your website traffic? Or, you may have noticed an increase or loss in eCommerce sales, email signups, or forms conversions. Sometimes, such a sudden increase can be fake and harmful to your site unless you’re running a specific campaign.</p>\n<p>Imagine you&#8217;re busy with something more important and weren’t checking your Analytics data for quite some time. Chances are your Analytics reports showed unusual spikes or drops in user interaction but you missed them. When you finally got back, you discovered a massive loss.</p>\n<p>Google Analytics custom alerts help to prevent such losses. You can set up alerts for certain changes in your Analytics data, so when the reports meet the threshold, Analytics immediately sends you an alert email. Then, you can instantly fix the issues.</p>\n<p>Google Analytics custom alerts are really useful as they help you to monitor huge changes in your Analytics reports and notify you immediately. Thus, you can instantly investigate and find out what’s causing the changes in your Analytics data. It protects you from some unfortunate conditions like referrer spam, loss in business, etc.</p>\n<p>Now, let’s go ahead and take a look at the process of creating custom alerts in Google Analytics.</p>\n<h3>Creating Custom Alerts in Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>To get started, make sure that you’ve signed into your Google Analytics account. Then, navigate to the <strong>Admin</strong> option at the bottom of your Analytics panel on the left.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169257\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg\" alt=\"ga-admin\" width=\"250\" height=\"586\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg 250w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin-128x300.jpg 128w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px\" /></p>\n<p>Upon clicking the Admin option, you’ll see 3 columns of settings there. Go to the <strong>View</strong> column and scroll down to the <strong>Custom Alerts</strong> option under <strong>Personal Tools and Assets</strong>. Click the Custom Alerts.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173368\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-custom-alerts-option.png\" alt=\"ga-custom-alerts-option\" width=\"620\" height=\"504\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-custom-alerts-option.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-custom-alerts-option-300x244.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see your custom alerts overview along with a <strong>New Alert</strong> button. If you haven’t created any custom alerts yet, you’ll see no items in the list. To create a new custom alert, click <strong>New Alert</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173369\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/new-ga-alert-button.png\" alt=\"new-ga-alert-button\" width=\"620\" height=\"322\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/new-ga-alert-button.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/new-ga-alert-button-300x156.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, you’ll see a page where you can add a new custom alert.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173370\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-alert-create-options.png\" alt=\"ga-alert-create-options\" width=\"620\" height=\"367\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-alert-create-options.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-alert-create-options-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>1. Alert name:</strong> First, enter an alert name.</p>\n<p><strong>2. Apply to:</strong> Then, choose the proper Analytics account from the <strong>Apply to</strong> option if you have more than 1 Analytics property.</p>\n<p><strong>3. Period:</strong> Next, you can select the frequency for the alert from the <strong>Period</strong> option. You can choose Day, Week, or Month. If you choose <strong>Day</strong>, it creates alerts based on daily changes in traffic or user interactions.</p>\n<p>Make sure to check <strong>Send me an email when this alert triggers.</strong> If you want to send the alert to other members of your team, you can add their email addresses from the <strong>Also include</strong> option. If you’re in the United States, you can also set up your mobile phone to receive a text message when the alert triggers.</p>\n<p><strong>4. Alert Conditions:</strong> In the <strong>Alert Conditions</strong>, you can set up following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>This applies to:</strong> You can select All Traffic or specific dimensions to which the alert applies.</li>\n<li><strong>Alert me when:</strong> Choose the metric to which the alert applies.</li>\n<li><strong>Condition:</strong> Condition options include Is less than, Is greater than, Decreases by more than, % Increases by more than, etc. If you aren’t sure about the average value of any metric, you can choose % Increases/ Decreases by more than option.</li>\n<li><strong>Value:</strong> Enter the value for the condition.</li>\n<li><strong>Compared to:</strong> If you choose % Increases/ Decreases by more than, you can choose comparing to previous day, week, or year.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For example, we created a new alert for bounce rate that triggers when it increases by more than 50% to the previous day. Take a look at the screenshot below:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173371\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-custom-alerts-ga.png\" alt=\"create-custom-alerts-for-bounce-rate-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"347\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-custom-alerts-ga.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-custom-alerts-ga-300x168.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Once you select all of your alert options, don’t forget to click the <strong>Save Alert</strong> button.</p>\n<p>That’s it! You’ve created a new alert in Google Analytics. Now you can create more alerts following the same process.</p>\n<p>Some of the important alerts can be a drop in sessions by more than 50%, unusual spike in website traffic, decrease in total revenue by more than 50%, etc.</p>\n<h3>Managing Your Google Analytics Custom Alerts</h3>\n<p>Managing Google Analytics custom alerts is as simple as creating one.</p>\n<p>As discussed above, you can find your list of custom alerts in the <strong>Custom Alerts</strong> option below the <strong>View</strong> column inside <strong>Admin</strong> options.</p>\n<p>All you need to do to edit a custom alert is to click on its name, then it’ll open the editor.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173372\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/click-custom-alert-to-edit.png\" alt=\"click-custom-alert-to-edit\" width=\"620\" height=\"155\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/click-custom-alert-to-edit.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/click-custom-alert-to-edit-300x75.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, you can make any changes you like. Once editing is complete, don’t forget to click <strong>Save Alert</strong>.</p>\n<h3>MonsterInsights Dashboard Reports vs. Custom Alerts</h3>\n<p>If you’re using <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights plugin</a> in WordPress for Google Analytics, it provides you with all your <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/google-analytics-dashboard/\">important reports right inside your WordPress dashboard</a>.</p>\n<p>If you’re always working on your dashboard, viewing Google Analytics reports is far easier for you with MonsterInsights&#8217; dashboard reports. With it, you may not even need to create custom alerts!</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-154753\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/dashboardwidget-full-width.png\" alt=\"Google Analytics Dashboard Widget for WordPress Full Screen\" width=\"620\" height=\"424\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/dashboardwidget-full-width.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/dashboardwidget-full-width-300x205.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> is the best Google Analytics plugin for WordPress. It makes Google Analytics easy for WordPress users from every aspect.</p>\n<p>For example, it’s easy to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">install Google Analytics using this plugin</a>. Setting up advanced tracking like <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/ecommerce/\">eCommerce</a>, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/forms/\">forms</a>, downloads, etc. is very easy as well. And, you can view extremely comprehensive reports directly from your dashboard.</p>\n<p>If you’re a solopreneur who works within WordPress dashboards most of the time, MonsterInsights&#8217; dashboard reports are the optimal tool for you.</p>\n<p>But, if you’re working off-site most of the time and rarely log into your WordPress dashboard or Google Analytics account, setting up custom alerts is a perfect solution.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to create and manage custom alerts in Google Analytics. You may also want to see our guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/\">how to view real-time reports in Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, don’t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-custom-alerts-in-google-analytics/\">How to Create Custom Alerts in Google Analytics (Beginner&#8217;s Guide)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\"